Adapting sample R code

2024-04-19

This code adapts sample R code from cdc dot gov and uses the survey package to run statistical tests, taking into account SDMVPSU (primary sampling unit), SDMVSTRA (stratum), and WTMEC2YR/WTMEC4YR (two or four-year mobile examination center exam weight).

library(dplyr)
library(survey)
library(corrplot)
options(survey.lonely.psu = "adjust")

cat("R package versions:\n")
for (p in c("base", "survey", "dplyr")) {
  cat(p, ": ", as.character(packageVersion(p)), "\n")
}

# Data preparation - Download & Read SAS Transport Files
# (DEMO) Demographic
download.file("https://wwwn.cdc.gov/Nchs/Nhanes/2015-2016/DEMO_I.XPT", tf <- tempfile(), mode = "wb")
DEMO_I <- foreign::read.xport(tf)[, c("SEQN", "RIAGENDR", "RIDAGEYR", "RIDRETH3", "SDMVSTRA", "SDMVPSU", "WTMEC2YR")]
nrow(DEMO_I)
length(unique(DEMO_I$SEQN))

# AUQ (Audiometry)
download.file("https://wwwn.cdc.gov/Nchs/Nhanes/2015-2016/AUQ_I.XPT", tf <- tempfile(), mode = "wb")
AUQ_I <- foreign::read.xport(tf)

# BMX (Body measures)
download.file("https://wwwn.cdc.gov/Nchs/Nhanes/2015-2016/BMX_I.XPT", tf <- tempfile(), mode = "wb")
BMX_I <- foreign::read.xport(tf)

# SLQ (Sleep disorders)
download.file("https://wwwn.cdc.gov/Nchs/Nhanes/2015-2016/SLQ_I.XPT", tf <- tempfile(), mode = "wb")
SLQ_I <- foreign::read.xport(tf)

# Appending Files and creating derived variables
result <- DEMO_I %>%
  left_join(AUQ_I, by = "SEQN") %>%
  left_join(BMX_I, by = "SEQN") %>%
  left_join(SLQ_I, by = "SEQN") %>%
  mutate(.,
    # create indicator for overall summary
    one = 1,
    Age = RIDAGEYR,
    Gender = factor(RIAGENDR, labels = c("Men", "Women")),
    Race = factor(RIDRETH3, labels=c("Mexican American", "Other Hispanic", "Non-Hispanic White", "Non-Hispanic Black", "Non-Hispanic Asian", "Other Race - Including Multi-Racial")),
    Age.Group = cut(RIDAGEYR, breaks = c(20, 39, 59, Inf), labels = c("20-39", "40-59", "60 and over")),
    Tinnitus = case_when(
      AUQ191 == "1" ~ "Yes",
      AUQ191 == "2" ~ "No"
    ),
    Ringing = if_else(AUQ191 %in% c(1, 2), if_else(AUQ191 == 2, 0, AUQ191), NA_real_),
    sleep.trouble = case_when(
      SLQ050 == 1 ~ "trouble sleeping",
      SLQ050 == 2 ~ "no trouble sleeping"
    ),
    inAnalysis = (RIDAGEYR >= 20 & !is.na(Ringing) & !is.na(sleep.trouble)),
  )

Defining a function to call svymean and unweighted count

# convenience function for generating unweighted count
getSummary <- function(varformula, byformula, design) {
  # Get mean, stderr, and unweighted sample size, mean, std error
  c <- svyby(varformula, byformula, design, unwtd.count)
  p <- svyby(varformula, byformula, design, svymean)
  outSum <- left_join(select(c, -se), p)
  outSum
}

# Calculate basic stats, by gender, by age group, and by age and gender
#' Adults
getSummary(~RIDAGEYR, ~one, NHANES)
#' By sex
getSummary(~RIDAGEYR, ~Gender, NHANES)
#' By age
getSummary(~RIDAGEYR, ~Age.Group, NHANES)
#' By sex and age
getSummary(~RIDAGEYR, ~ Gender + Age.Group, NHANES)

chi_squared_gender_table <- svytable(~ Gender + Tinnitus, design = NHANES)
chi_squared_gender_table

## Gender        No      Yes

prop.table(chi_squared_gender_table) # to convert the above to proportions
##        Tinnitus
## Gender         No       Yes
##   Men   0.4014061 0.0872450
##   Women 0.4375878 0.0737611
# plot(chi_squared_gender_table)

chi_squared_gender <- svychisq(~ Gender + Tinnitus, design = NHANES)
chi_squared_gender
## 
##  Pearson's X^2: Rao & Scott adjustment
## 
## data:  svychisq(~Gender + Tinnitus, design = NHANES)
## F = 4.657, ndf = 1, ddf = 15, p-value = 0.04755
residuals_gender <- residuals(chi_squared_gender)
print(residuals_gender)
##        Tinnitus
## Gender          No        Yes
##   Men   -0.9238314  2.1088756
##   Women  0.9030951 -2.0615398
corrplot(residuals_gender, is.cor = FALSE, cl.pos = "b", cl.length = 5, insig = "blank", method = "circle", addCoef.col = "white", number.cex = 0.8, title = "Chi-Squared residuals for Gender ~ Tinnitus",mar=c(0,0,2,0))

barplot(residuals_gender, beside = TRUE, legend.text = TRUE, args.legend = list(title = "~Gender + Tinnitus Residuals"))
